abstract = {Minimal residual disease (MRD) is known to be an independent prognostic factor in patients with acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL). High-throughput sequencing (HTS) is currently used in routine practice for the diagnosis and follow-up of patients with hematological neoplasms. In this retrospective study, we examined the role of immunoglobulin/T-cell receptor-based MRD in patients with ALL by HTS analysis of immunoglobulin H and/or T-cell receptor gamma chain loci in bone marrow samples from 11 patients with ALL, at diagnosis and during follow-up. We assessed the clinical feasibility of using combined HTS and bioinformatics analysis with interactive visualization using Vidjil software. We discuss the advantages and drawbacks of HTS for monitoring MRD. HTS gives a more complete insight of the leukemic population than conventional real-time quantitative PCR (qPCR), and allows identification of new emerging clones at each time point of the monitoring. Thus, HTS monitoring of Ig/TCR based MRD is expected to improve the management of patients with ALL.},
