@article{Faham2017,
abstract = {OBJECTIVE: To investigate the clinical presentation and medical treatment of patients with systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis (sJIA) during first year of illness. Our study focused on three-year outcomes in a longitudinally followed sub-cohort. METHODS: From 2000 to 2013, 597 sJIA patients with disease duration of ≤12 months were recorded in the National Pediatric Rheumatologic Database (NPRD). Among those, three-year outcome data were available for 133 patients. This included the clinical Juvenile Arthritis Disease Activity Score (cJADAS-10) and the physicians' global assessment score, as well as assessment of joint involvement, growth retardation and patient-reported outcomes. RESULTS: The median cJADAS-10 significantly declined from seven in 2000 to two in 2013, while the proportion of patients with inactive disease increased from 19{\%} in 2000 to 41{\%} in 2013. Treatment with systemic glucocorticoids and disease modifying anti-rheumatic drugs (DMARDs) remained stable over the period. In 2013, the proportion of patients treated with biological DMARDs increased to 20{\%} of sJIA patients. Three years post onset, 72{\%} of sJIA patients achieved inactive disease and 75{\%} had no functional limitations. Growth retardation was associated with persistently high disease activity and continuing use of systemic glucocorticoids. At the three-year follow-up, one-third of patients were still being treated with systemic glucocorticoids. CONCLUSION: The proportion of patients achieving inactive disease has increased over the last decade. Possible explanations may include improved access to specialized care, additional treatment options, and earlier or faster step-up treatment. However, challenges in sJIA management remain, as approximately 30{\%} of patients continue to present with ongoing, active disease. This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.},
